title: Update to URI.d.ts
body: uri.search(true) does return an object, but Typescript believes there is a difference between an Object and any.  Thus, if your querystring includes ?myParam=myValue, you should be able to access the value using uri.search(true).myParam.  However, the compiler threw the error "The property 'myParam' does not exist on on value of type 'Object'".  Changing the return type to any fixes this.

title: Fix Angular externs to work with TS 1.4
body:
Merge the IAngularStatic and the angular namespace by moving all type definitions into the main "angular" module.
This fixes compatibility with TypeScript 1.4 (see issue #3656 and issue #3670), and allow depending on the definitions using "require" style imports instead of <reference> style.

The drawback is that this is a compatibility breaking change. Existing clients must replace all occurences of "ng." in their code base with "angular.", for example by running `sed -i 's|\bng\.|angular.|g'` or something similar over their entire code base.

I don't see another reasonable way to create compatibility with TS 1.4 - any other ideas that'd maintain backwards compatibility? Maybe it'd be possible to declare a `var ng = angular;` in a compatibility shim?

In order to test my changes, I replaced the tests in chai-tests.ts with those from the tests for both the [assert](https://github.com/chaijs/chai/blob/v2.0.0/test/assert.js) and [expect](https://github.com/chaijs/chai/blob/v2.0.0/test/expect.js) assertion APIs in the chai repository (with as few changes as possible to make them valid TypeScript). I assume the test coverage is a bit better with this change but I know a few things are still missing such as the _should_ assertion API (see #3524).

Ideally I would have pulled in @otiai10's good work so that the _should_ assertion style was also covered but I figured this PR was big enough as is. I will save that for next time.
